el and Scientific Computing},\n  volume = {7782},\n  series = {Lecture Notes in Computer Science},\n  editor = {Manninen, Pekka and \\\"Oster, Per},\n  doi = {10.1007/978-3-642-36803-5_34},\n  title = {{P}arallel {I}nterval {N}ewton {M}ethod on {CUDA}},\n  url = {<a target=\"blank\" href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36803-5_34\">http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36803-5_34</a>},\n  publisher = {Springer Berlin Heidelberg},\n  keywords = {Interval arithmetic; Interval Newton method; Parallel computing; Load balancing; CUDA; GPGPU},\n  author = {Beck, Philip-Daniel and Nehmeier, Marco},\n  pages = {454-464},\n  language = {English},\n  pdf = {<a target=\"blank\" href=\"http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/761.pdf\">http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/761.pdf</a>}\n}\n</pre>\n\n','In this paper we discuss a parallel variant of the interval Newton method for root finding of non linear continuously differentiable functions on the CUDA architecture. For this purpose we have investigated different dynamic load balancing methods to get an evenly balanced workload during the parallel computation. We tested the functionality, correctness and performance of our implementation in different case studies and compared it with other implementations.','{P}arallel {I}nterval {N}ewton {M}ethod on {CUDA}',0,0,2013,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,'0000-00-00 00:00:00','2016-06-01 09:41:03',0),(762,'paper','nehmeierPPAM2011','incollection','@incollection{nehmeierPPAM2011,\n  abstract = {In this paper we discuss the interaction of expression templates with OpenCL devices. We show how the expression tree of expression templates can be used to generate problem specific OpenCL kernels. In a second approach we use expression templates to optimize the data transfer between the host and the device which leads to a measurable performance increase in a domain specific language approach. We tested the functionality, correctness and performance for both implementations in a case study for vector and matrix operations.},\n  year = {2012},\n  isbn = {978-3-642-31499-5},\n  booktitle = {Parallel Processing and Applied Mathematics},\n  volume = {7204},\n  series = {Lecture Notes in Computer Science},\n  editor = {Wyrzykowski, Roman and Dongarra, Jack and Karczewski, Konrad and Wa\\\'sniewski, Jerzy},\n  doi = {10.1007/978-3-642-31500-8_8},\n  title = {{E}xpression {T}emplates and {OpenCL}},\n  url = {http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-31500-8_8},\n  publisher = {Springer Berlin Heidelberg},\n  keywords = {GPGPU; OpenCL; C++; Expression templates; Domain specific language; Code generation},\n  author = {Bawidamann, Uwe and Nehmeier, Marco},\n  pages = {71-80},\n  language = {English},\n  pdf = {http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/762.pdf},\n}\n\n','\n\nUwe Bawidamann and Marco Nehmeier.\nExpression Templates and OpenCL.\nIn <em>Parallel Processing and Applied Mathematics</em>, Roman\nWyrzykowski, Jack Dongarra, Konrad Karczewski, and Jerzy Wa&#x15b;niewski,\neditors, volume 7204 of <em>Lecture Notes in Computer Science</em>, pages\n71-80. Springer Berlin Heidelberg, 2012.\n[&nbsp;<a class=\"abstract-a\" onclick=\"showAbstract(\'bib-of-nehmeierPPAM2011\')\">bib</a>&nbsp;| <a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-31500-8_8\" target=\"blank\">DOI</a>&nbsp;| <a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-31500-8_8\" target=\"blank\">http</a>&nbsp;| <a href=\"http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/762.pdf\" target=\"blank\">.pdf</a>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a class=\"abstract-a\" onclick=\"showAbstract(\'nehmeierPPAM2011\')\">Abstract</a>&nbsp; ] <div id=\"bib-of-nehmeierPPAM2011\" class=\"inline-bib\" style=\"display:none;\"><pre>\n@incollection{nehmeierPPAM2011,\nabstract = {In this paper we discuss the interaction of expression templates with OpenCL devices. We show how the expression tree of expression templates can be used to generate problem specific OpenCL kernels. In a second approach we use expression templates to optimize the data transfer between the host and the device which leads to a measurable performance increase in a domain specific language approach. We tested the functionality, correctness and performance for both implementations in a case study for vector and matrix operations.},\nyear = {2012},\nisbn = {978-3-642-31499-5},\nbooktitle = {Parallel Processing and Applied Mathematics},\nvolume = {7204},\nseries = {Lecture Notes in Computer Science},\neditor = {Wyrzykowski, Roman and Dongarra, Jack and Karczewski, Konrad and Wa\\\'sniewski, Jerzy},\ndoi = {10.1007/978-3-642-31500-8_8},\ntitle = {{E}xpression {T}emplates and {OpenCL}},\nurl = {<a target=\"blank\" href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-31500-8_8\">http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-31500-8_8</a>},\npublisher = {Springer Berlin Heidelberg},\nkeywords = {GPGPU; OpenCL; C++; Expression templates; Domain specific language; Code generation},\nauthor = {Bawidamann, Uwe and Nehmeier, Marco},\npages = {71-80},\nlanguage = {English},\npdf = {<a target=\"blank\" href=\"http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/762.pdf\">http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/762.pdf</a>}\n}\n</pre>\n</div> <div id=\"nehmeierPPAM2011\" style=\"display:none;\"><blockquote class=\"abstractBQ\">\nIn this paper we discuss the interaction of expression templates with OpenCL devices. We show how the expression tree of expression templates can be used to generate problem specific OpenCL kernels. In a second approach we use expression templates to optimize the data transfer between the host and the device which leads to a measurable performance increase in a domain specific language approach. We tested the functionality, correctness and performance for both implementations in a case study for vector and matrix operations.\n</blockquote></div>\n','<a name=\"nehmeierPPAM2011\"></a><pre>\n@incollection{nehmeierPPAM2011,\n  abstract = {In this paper we discuss the interaction of expression templates with OpenCL devices. We show how the expression tree of expression templates can be used to generate problem specific OpenCL kernels. In a second approach we use expression templates to optimize the data transfer between the host and the device which leads to a measurable performance increase in a domain specific language approach. We tested the functionality, correctness and performance for both implementations in a case study for vector and matrix operations.},\n  year = {2012},\n  isbn = {978-3-642-31499-5},\n  booktitle = {Parallel Processing and Applied Mathematics},\n  volume = {7204},\n  series = {Lecture Notes in Computer Science},\n  editor = {Wyrzykowski, Roman and Dongarra, Jack and Karczewski, Konrad and Wa\\\'sniewski, Jerzy},\n  doi = {10.1007/978-3-642-31500-8_8},\n  title = {{E}xpression {T}emplates and {OpenCL}},\n  url = {<a target=\"blank\" href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-31500-8_8\">http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-31500-8_8</a>},\n  publisher = {Springer Berlin Heidelberg},\n  keywords = {GPGPU; OpenCL; C++; Expression templates; Domain specific language; Code generation},\n  author = {Bawidamann, Uwe and Nehmeier, Marco},\n  pages = {71-80},\n  language = {English},\n  pdf = {<a target=\"blank\" href=\"http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/762.pdf\">http://se2.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de/pa/publications/download/paper/762.pdf</a>}\n}\n</pre>\n\n','In this paper we discuss the interaction of expression templates with OpenCL devices. We show how the expression tree of expression templates can be used to generate problem specific OpenCL kernels. In a second approach we use expression templates to optimize the data transfer between the host and the device which leads to a measurable performance increase in a domain specific language approach. We tested the functionality, correctness and performance for both im